<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,152,323]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,189,215]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles the foregoing species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen in Chen &amp; Maca" authorityYear="2012" box="[943,1080,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biclavata">
<emphasis box="[943,960,190,215]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[976,1080,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">biclavata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in having the aedeagal sheath with two marginally serrated postgonites on left lateral lobe and one anterior, large, marginally serrated postgonite and posterior, small, not serrated one on right lobe. However, these two species can be distinguished from each other by their diagnoses.
</paragraph>
